  • So we know that a Holt-Winterâ€™s model with additive trend, multiplicative seasonality (and multiplicative error) is the preferred Holt-Winterâ€™s model structure. \(\color{red}{\text{Now can we tune the gamma smoothing parameter to find the optimal Holt-Winterâ€™s model? }}\)

Data Example (contâ€™d)

  • Step 8 :Identify optimal gamma Vector of values from 0.0001 to 0.95 with step 0.01 ( The gamma parameter captures seasonality. We can identify the gamma that reduces forecast error).
gamma <- seq(0.0001, 0.95, 0.01)
  • Initialization of variable RMSE with a single value NA. Later variable RMSE will be a vector containing sums of squared errors for different values of gamma.
RMSE <- NA
  • Iterate through all values of vector gamma.
for(i in seq_along(gamma)) {
  hw.opt <- ets(train, "MAM", gamma = gamma[i])
  future <- forecast(hw.opt, h = 12)
  RMSE[i] = accuracy(future, test)[2,2]
}
  • Plot of sums of squared errors calculated for different values gamma.
error <- data_frame(gamma, RMSE)
minimum <- filter(error, RMSE == min(RMSE))
minimum
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   gamma  RMSE
##   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 0.560  284.
ggplot(error, aes(gamma, RMSE)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point(data = minimum, color = "blue", size = 2) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 360)) +
  ggtitle("gamma's impact on forecast errors",
          subtitle = "gamma =0.560 minimizes RMSE")

Data Example (contâ€™d)

  • Step 9 : Apply Holt-Winterâ€™s exponential smoothing with optimal gamma:
hw.opt <- ets(train, "MAM", gamma = 0.560)
  • Compare on forecasted values:
for.mult3 <- forecast(hw.opt, h = 12)
